1
00:00:03,250 --> 00:00:06,150
Most option traders start out buying options because

2
00:00:06,150 --> 00:00:07,690
it's simplest to understand.

3
00:00:08,330 --> 00:00:10,010
If you think Facebook stock will go up,

4
00:00:10,250 --> 00:00:11,750
you could buy a call, and if you

5
00:00:11,750 --> 00:00:13,670
think Facebook stock will go down, you could

6
00:00:13,670 --> 00:00:14,290
buy a put.

7
00:00:15,070 --> 00:00:16,870
This sounds great because you can trade the

8
00:00:16,870 --> 00:00:19,270
options with much less capital than if you

9
00:00:19,270 --> 00:00:20,610
were to simply trade the stock.

10
00:00:21,010 --> 00:00:21,990
Let me show you an example.

11
00:00:22,530 --> 00:00:24,150
First, let's look at an option chain on

12
00:00:24,150 --> 00:00:27,250
stock XYZ, which is currently trading at $75

13
00:00:27,250 --> 00:00:28,290
per share.

14
00:00:28,790 --> 00:00:30,370
Let's say you are bullish on the stock

15
00:00:30,370 --> 00:00:32,250
and you're looking to buy a call option,

16
00:00:33,110 --> 00:00:34,150
so we're just going to go ahead and

17
00:00:34,150 --> 00:00:35,430
ignore the put options for now.

18
00:00:35,750 --> 00:00:37,670
If you were to buy the 70 strike

19
00:00:37,670 --> 00:00:40,270
call option, for example, this would cost you

20
00:00:40,270 --> 00:00:43,690
$750, and you're hoping that the price of

21
00:00:43,690 --> 00:00:45,890
XYZ will rise so you can make money,

22
00:00:46,350 --> 00:00:48,170
but this is not a very good trading

23
00:00:48,170 --> 00:00:50,490
strategy because it puts time decay against you,

24
00:00:50,590 --> 00:00:52,770
and not only does the price of XYZ

25
00:00:52,770 --> 00:00:54,490
have to move up, it has to move

26
00:00:54,490 --> 00:00:56,410
up a significant amount for you to even

27
00:00:56,410 --> 00:00:56,950
break even.

28
00:00:57,490 --> 00:00:59,250
In this case, your break even is at

29
00:00:59,250 --> 00:01:01,790
$77.50, a full two and a half

30
00:01:01,790 --> 00:01:04,610
points above the current stock price, and if

31
00:01:04,610 --> 00:01:07,410
XYZ sits still and trades sideways, you're screwed

32
00:01:07,410 --> 00:01:09,670
because your option you just bought will decay

33
00:01:09,670 --> 00:01:10,730
each and every day.

34
00:01:11,270 --> 00:01:12,730
And that's what options are, guys.

35
00:01:12,870 --> 00:01:16,230
They are depreciating assets, and any smart investor

36
00:01:16,230 --> 00:01:18,330
is not going to buy a depreciating asset

37
00:01:18,330 --> 00:01:19,570
and call it an investment.

38
00:01:20,090 --> 00:01:21,370
Let me show you a better way that

39
00:01:21,370 --> 00:01:23,230
allows you to make a directional bet on

40
00:01:23,230 --> 00:01:24,990
the stock, but without having to buy a

41
00:01:24,990 --> 00:01:26,890
naked option or put up tons of capital

42
00:01:26,890 --> 00:01:28,170
to trade the stock itself.

43
00:01:28,690 --> 00:01:30,890
And we're actually going to eliminate time decay

44
00:01:30,890 --> 00:01:31,590
altogether.

45
00:01:31,930 --> 00:01:34,330
Instead of just buying the 70 strike call

46
00:01:34,330 --> 00:01:36,170
option, we're going to do something a little

47
00:01:36,170 --> 00:01:36,690
bit different.

48
00:01:37,110 --> 00:01:38,710
We're going to buy this option, but we're

49
00:01:38,710 --> 00:01:41,670
also going to simultaneously sell a cheaper out

50
00:01:41,670 --> 00:01:43,830
-of-the-money option to reduce our cost.

51
00:01:44,130 --> 00:01:46,150
So in this case, we're going to buy

52
00:01:46,150 --> 00:01:49,450
the 70 strike call for $750, but we're

53
00:01:49,450 --> 00:01:51,450
also going to sell the 80 strike call

54
00:01:51,450 --> 00:01:52,630
for $250.

55
00:01:53,270 --> 00:01:55,350
This knocks our cost down by a full

56
00:01:55,350 --> 00:01:58,170
$250, and our net price is now just

57
00:01:58,170 --> 00:01:58,670
$500.

58
00:01:59,450 --> 00:02:01,970
This is called buying a vertical spread.

59
00:02:02,370 --> 00:02:04,870
By trading a vertical spread rather than simply

60
00:02:04,870 --> 00:02:07,690
buying a single option, we're able to significantly

61
00:02:07,690 --> 00:02:10,310
reduce the cost of our trade, which improves

62
00:02:10,310 --> 00:02:12,470
our breakeven on the trade and our probability

63
00:02:12,470 --> 00:02:12,950
of success.

64
00:02:13,290 --> 00:02:15,250
The net price we pay for this vertical

65
00:02:15,250 --> 00:02:18,470
spread is $5, so our breakeven is at

66
00:02:18,470 --> 00:02:20,930
$75 per share, which is where the current

67
00:02:20,930 --> 00:02:21,810
stock price is.

68
00:02:22,290 --> 00:02:23,430
If you're lost, hang with me.

69
00:02:23,490 --> 00:02:24,770
I'm going to show you how this works.

70
00:02:25,350 --> 00:02:27,990
Let's compare the two strategies in three different

71
00:02:27,990 --> 00:02:28,570
scenarios.

72
00:02:29,310 --> 00:02:30,370
Scenario number one.

73
00:02:30,810 --> 00:02:33,450
XYZ stock price has moved up, and at

74
00:02:33,450 --> 00:02:36,630
the expiration date, it's at $79.50 per

75
00:02:36,630 --> 00:02:36,990
share.

76
00:02:37,590 --> 00:02:39,790
First, let's look at the 70-80 vertical

77
00:02:39,790 --> 00:02:40,310
spread.

78
00:02:40,610 --> 00:02:42,430
The short 80 call that you sold for

79
00:02:42,430 --> 00:02:45,010
$250 would now be worthless because it's out

80
00:02:45,010 --> 00:02:45,430
-of-the-money.

81
00:02:45,970 --> 00:02:48,510
So you made $250 on the short 80

82
00:02:48,510 --> 00:02:51,250
call, and the long 70 call you bought

83
00:02:51,250 --> 00:02:54,410
for $7.50 is now $9.50 in

84
00:02:54,410 --> 00:02:57,730
the money, so it's worth $9.50. So

85
00:02:57,730 --> 00:03:00,390
you made $200 on the long 70 call,

86
00:03:00,610 --> 00:03:03,090
so your net profit is $450.

87
00:03:04,310 --> 00:03:06,390
Now remember, the net price we paid for

88
00:03:06,390 --> 00:03:09,490
the vertical spread was $500, so our return

89
00:03:09,490 --> 00:03:11,530
on capital was 90%.

90
00:03:11,530 --> 00:03:14,070
Our max risk was simply the net price

91
00:03:14,070 --> 00:03:15,950
we bought the spread for, which was $500.

92
00:03:16,730 --> 00:03:18,950
Now let's compare this to if we simply

93
00:03:18,950 --> 00:03:22,270
bought the 70 call for $7.50. With

94
00:03:22,270 --> 00:03:24,690
the stock at $79.50, our long call

95
00:03:24,690 --> 00:03:27,030
would be at $9.50, providing us with

96
00:03:27,030 --> 00:03:29,670
a profit of $200, so our return on

97
00:03:29,670 --> 00:03:34,030
capital was only 26.67%. Our max risk

98
00:03:34,030 --> 00:03:37,390
was $750 we paid to buy this option.

99
00:03:37,810 --> 00:03:39,450
Let's look at scenario two.

100
00:03:40,070 --> 00:03:42,910
XYZ has mostly traded sideways, and at the

101
00:03:42,910 --> 00:03:45,550
expiration date, the price is still at $75

102
00:03:45,550 --> 00:03:46,490
per share.

103
00:03:46,950 --> 00:03:49,390
Looking at the vertical spread, our long 70

104
00:03:49,390 --> 00:03:52,590
call will now be worth $5, resulting in

105
00:03:52,590 --> 00:03:55,250
a loss of $250 on that leg of

106
00:03:55,250 --> 00:03:55,690
the trade.

107
00:03:55,990 --> 00:03:58,190
But our short 80 call will again be

108
00:03:58,190 --> 00:04:01,510
worthless, resulting in a profit of $250 on

109
00:04:01,510 --> 00:04:02,050
that leg.

110
00:04:02,510 --> 00:04:04,210
So the two cancel out, and we would

111
00:04:04,210 --> 00:04:05,790
actually just be at break-even on the

112
00:04:05,790 --> 00:04:06,070
trade.

113
00:04:06,650 --> 00:04:08,550
Now compare that to if we simply bought

114
00:04:08,550 --> 00:04:11,450
the 70 call at $7.50. We would

115
00:04:11,450 --> 00:04:13,990
now be sitting on a $250 loss.

116
00:04:14,610 --> 00:04:16,130
So in the case of the vertical spread,

117
00:04:16,470 --> 00:04:18,410
time decay was not an issue whatsoever.

118
00:04:19,190 --> 00:04:21,290
However, if you just bought the 70 call

119
00:04:21,290 --> 00:04:24,070
rather than trading the vertical spread, you're sitting

120
00:04:24,070 --> 00:04:26,270
on a 33% loss due to time

121
00:04:26,270 --> 00:04:26,590
decay.

122
00:04:27,290 --> 00:04:28,510
Okay, scenario three.

123
00:04:29,150 --> 00:04:31,410
We are completely wrong about the direction of

124
00:04:31,410 --> 00:04:34,050
XYZ, and the stock tanks down to $50

125
00:04:34,050 --> 00:04:35,010
per share.

126
00:04:35,410 --> 00:04:37,390
Both of the options that make up our

127
00:04:37,390 --> 00:04:39,590
vertical spread are out of the money and

128
00:04:39,590 --> 00:04:40,110
are worthless.

129
00:04:40,890 --> 00:04:43,410
So we lost $750 on the long 70

130
00:04:43,410 --> 00:04:45,870
call, but we made $250 on the short

131
00:04:45,870 --> 00:04:46,430
80 call.

132
00:04:46,650 --> 00:04:50,370
So our net loss is $500, much less

133
00:04:50,370 --> 00:04:53,550
than losing $750 like we would have if

134
00:04:53,550 --> 00:04:55,150
we were to simply buy the 70 strike

135
00:04:55,150 --> 00:04:55,450
call.

136
00:04:56,190 --> 00:04:58,650
Buying the vertical was better than buying the

137
00:04:58,650 --> 00:05:01,410
naked option in all three of these scenarios,

138
00:05:01,830 --> 00:05:04,390
but there is one scenario where buying the

139
00:05:04,390 --> 00:05:06,050
naked call would have worked out better.

140
00:05:06,810 --> 00:05:08,890
Let's say the stock rips higher and is

141
00:05:08,890 --> 00:05:11,590
now at $85 per share at the expiration

142
00:05:11,590 --> 00:05:11,970
date.

143
00:05:12,350 --> 00:05:14,570
For the vertical, the 70 call we bought

144
00:05:14,570 --> 00:05:17,110
for $7.50 would now be worth $15,

145
00:05:17,610 --> 00:05:20,790
providing us with a profit of $750 on

146
00:05:20,790 --> 00:05:21,330
that leg.

147
00:05:21,630 --> 00:05:23,610
And the short 80 call we sold at

148
00:05:23,610 --> 00:05:26,390
$250 would now be worth $5, resulting in

149
00:05:26,390 --> 00:05:28,610
a loss of $250 on this leg of

150
00:05:28,610 --> 00:05:29,010
the trade.

151
00:05:29,510 --> 00:05:32,990
So our net profit is only $500 as

152
00:05:32,990 --> 00:05:35,790
opposed to $750 if we would have just

153
00:05:35,790 --> 00:05:36,390
bought the call.

154
00:05:36,890 --> 00:05:38,890
So that's the only downfall with the vertical

155
00:05:38,890 --> 00:05:41,390
spread, is that it has limited profit potential.

156
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:44,570
Whereas buying the naked option allows us unlimited

157
00:05:44,570 --> 00:05:45,570
profit potential.

158
00:05:45,950 --> 00:05:48,250
But is the profit potential really unlimited?

159
00:05:48,810 --> 00:05:49,610
Of course not.

160
00:05:49,690 --> 00:05:52,990
That's just theoretical because theoretically a stock can

161
00:05:52,990 --> 00:05:54,030
go to infinity.

162
00:05:54,710 --> 00:05:56,810
But look, you still made a 100%

163
00:05:56,810 --> 00:05:59,330
return on capital on the vertical spread, so

164
00:05:59,330 --> 00:06:00,590
what is there to be upset about?

165
00:06:01,130 --> 00:06:03,550
And trust me, these three scenarios are going

166
00:06:03,550 --> 00:06:05,810
to happen way more often and the vertical

167
00:06:05,810 --> 00:06:07,410
spread will pay you far more in the

168
00:06:07,410 --> 00:06:09,230
long run than the few times you might

169
00:06:09,230 --> 00:06:11,090
eventually hit a home run with buying the

170
00:06:11,090 --> 00:06:11,710
naked option.

